{
  "card_id": "continuation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Continuation",
  "aliases": [
    "Continuation Entry",
    "continuation entry",
    "continuation move",
    "Continuation Move"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A trade entry taken after a protected swing has formed, when price retraces into a point of interest (e.g., fair value gap, order block) and then closes through the series of opposing candles, confirming a change in state of delivery. This allows participation in the established trend direction after the initial reversal, providing improved risk-to-reward and higher-probability alignment within the fractal model.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Confirm the higher time frame directional bias and ensure the market is in an expansion or trending phase (e.g., daily/weekly candle closures pointing toward a liquidity target).",
    "Identify a prior protected swing (swing low for longs, swing high for shorts) confirmed by a change in state of delivery (CISD) — i.e., a closure through the series of opposing candles.",
    "Wait for price to retrace into a valid point of interest, such as a fair value gap, order block, propulsion block, or the equilibrium/T-spot of the opposing candle series; retracements should be shallow, not deep (expansion into expansion signals reversal).",
    "Confirm the continuation trigger: a candle closes through the series of opposing candles (down-close for bullish, up-close for bearish) into that point of interest, forming a new protected swing; the closure should be swift (1-3 candles) and aggressive, not slow or resembling consolidation.",
    "Align entry with the open of a new higher time frame candle to ensure fresh range for expansion; avoid entering late within an expansion candle that has already exhausted its range.",
    "Place a stop loss beyond the newly formed protected swing low/high, ensuring a minimum 2R target is available to the next drawn-on liquidity (e.g., previous day high/low, external range liquidity); skip if 2R is not achievable.",
    "If the lower time frame structure is messy or lacks a clean point of interest, step up one time frame (e.g., 1H to 4H) to find a clearer continuation; do not force entries without a valid POI.",
    "Avoid taking continuation entries after the initial target or external liquidity has already been hit, as a new phase of price (reversal/range) is likely; also avoid if the move forms a sideways consolidation rather than a V-shaped recovery."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Continuation entries are the preferred trade type in the fractal model because they confirm trend direction, reduce stop size by anchoring on freshly formed protected swings at points of interest, and enforce a systematic 2R+ risk-to-reward. They allow traders to join an established move after the initial reversal, aligning higher time frame bias with lower time frame triggers. Typical execution: identify HTF bias and protected swing, wait for retracement into a PD array, confirm with a closure through opposing candles, enter on the new swing, and target external liquidity.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering without a confirmed closure through the series of opposing candles, relying on a wick, sweep, or a single candle without full CISD confirmation.",
    "Taking entries without a valid protected swing already in place, or mistaking an unprotected swing for a continuation setup.",
    "Mistaking a deep retracement (expansion meeting expansion) or a sideways consolidation for a continuation setup, whereas these often signal reversal or manipulation.",
    "Entering without price retracing into a clearly defined point of interest, or treating a closure that fails to reach a valid POI as acceptable.",
    "Chasing the move late within an expansion candle, after the higher time frame target has already been hit, or entering after multiple expansion candles have printed, instead of waiting for the open of a new higher time frame candle.",
    "Entering when the retracement sweep of a short-term level forms a higher time frame wick, which often leads to a counter-CISD and reversal rather than a continuation.",
    "Failing to ensure a minimum 2R target is achievable with the stop placed on the new protected swing; entering when the stop is too wide or not adjusting stop placement accordingly.",
    "Treating a slow or shallow closure through opposing candles as valid, when the structure is actually a consolidation or manipulation lacking aggression.",
    "Forcing entries on a messy lower time frame without stepping up to a cleaner higher time frame where structures and points of interest are better defined.",
    "Taking entries against the existing higher time frame bias or prematurely switching bias on a single counter-move without confirmation of a true reversal (expansion-met-with-expansion)."
  ],
